The '''Montana Dinosaur Trail''' is a series of fourteen [[dinosaur]]-themed [[museums]], [[state parks]] and other attractions in twelve communities located in the central and eastern regions of the state of [[Montana]] in the [[United States|United States of America]].<ref>Montana Office of Tourism</ref> The trail, a plan to increase attendance at the region's museums and drive tourism in general was established via the work of a number of museums as well as community and state officials.<ref name="jur">{{Cite web|url=http://www.greatfallstribune.com/news/stories/20040627/localnews/729423.html|title=Jurassic Journey: Follow the Dinosaur Trail|accessdate=2008-05-27|date=2004-06-27|author=Karen Ogden|work=The Great Falls Tribune}}</ref> The idea for a trail uniting the museums and promoting [[tourism]] in eastern Montana came from a meeting of the [[Missouri River]] Country [[board of directors]] at the Dinosaur Field Station in [[Malta, Montana]] and the trail was officially launched via the efforts of the tourism groups of: Custer Country, Missouri River Country, Russell Country and Yellowstone Country; two state agencies: Fish, Wildlife and Parks and [[Travel Montana]]; and two federal agencies: the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] and the [[Bureau of Land Management]].<ref name="dinot">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newwest.net/index.php/topic/article/dino_trail_is_tourism_home_run/C41/L41/|title=Dino Trail is Tourism Home Run|accessdate=2008-05-27|date=2007-07-28|author=Bill Schneider|work=The New West Magazine}}</ref>
The Dinosaur Trail opened in May 2005 and drew more than 196,000 visitors its first year.<ref>[https://docs.google.com/document/d/1whnoLeMElFQPYxN--7K2wMIEnWdxcIhmO4Px-kGvoyM/edit?hl=en_US What Happened Along the MT Dinosaur Trail in 2005], annual trail report produced by MT Office of Tourism</ref> Since its opening, the trail facilities have hosted between 236,000 and 302,000 visitors each year.<ref>MT Office of Tourism statistics from MT Dino Trail Annual Reports</ref> Promotion of the Trail includes a "Prehistoric [[Passport]]" on which visitors collect dinosaur icon stamps from each museum they visit.<ref name="jur"/> In addition to the participating museums, the trail has helped increase visitors to other small businesses along the route.<ref name="attr">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/destinations/2005-08-01-montana-dinosaurs_x.htm|title=Dinosaur Trail Helping Attract More Tourists|accessdate=2008-05-27|date=2005-08-01|work=USA Today}}</ref>
==Participating organizations== The fourteen organizations that make up the Montana Dinosaur Trail are the following: {{col-begin}} {{col-break}} *[http://www.blainecountymuseum.com Blaine County Museum] *[[Carter County Museum]] *[[Fort Peck Interpretive Center]] *[http://www.garfieldcounty.com/museum.html Garfield County Museum] *[[Great Plains Dinosaur Museum and Field Station]] *[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719063339/http://www.havremt.com/attractions/h_earl_clack_museum.htm H. Earl Clack Memorial Museum] *[[Makoshika Dinosaur Museum]] {{col-break}} *[[Makoshika State Park]] *[[Museum of the Rockies]] *[http://oldtrailmuseum.org/ Old Trail Museum] *[http://www.phillipscountymuseum.org Phillips County Museum] *[http://www.rudyardmuseum.com Rudyard Depot Museum] *[[Two Medicine Dinosaur Center]] *[http://www.harlowtonmuseum.com Upper Musselshell Museum] {{col-end}}
